teric writing in the work of four of the first kabbalistic authors—Abraham ben David, Isaac the Blind, Ezra ben Solomon, and Asher ben David—and thereby helps recast our understanding of the earliest stages of kabbalistic literary history.The book will interest scholars in Jewish mysticism and Jewish philosophy, as well as those working in medieval Jewish history. Throughout, Jonathan V. Dauber has endeavored to write an accessible work that does not require extensive prior knowledge of kabbalistic thought. Accordingly, it finds points of contact between scholars of various religious traditions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aCabalaxHistory. 0aJewish literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aJudaismxHistoryyMedieval and early modern period, 425-1789. 0aMysticismxJudaismxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aSecrecy in literature. 0aSecrecyxReligious aspectsxJudaism. 4aHistory of Jewish People and Culture. 4aInterdisciplinary-Jewish Studies. 4aReligion-Judaism. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / Kabbalah & Mysticism.2bisacsh  aAbraham b. David.  aAsher b. David.  aEsotericism.  aEzra b. Solomon of Gerona.  aIsaac the Blind.  aKabbalah.  aLeo Strauss.  aSecrecy.  aanagram.  acode.  aliterary device.  amedieval Jewish history.  amysticism.  aoccult.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076767440uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/9781512822762?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781512822762423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781512822762/original  a978-3-11-076767-4  University of Pennsylvania Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  